	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10332027082704><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=10332027082704>RE: research</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=10332027082704#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73372><span id=Scholar>Malaclypse</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>116 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Sep 28th 5:01 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>ok, couple things. If I read your argument right the concordance stuff is worth doing because of the friends you gain while wandering around collecting components, correct?<br><br>Now, that may well be true and if that works for ya, great. And granted when I did my first concordance combine I thought it was kind of neat. bit of a hassle.. but neat. Rounded up all me parts, camped fire beatle eyes and all the other stuff for the first level of reasearch, (too tired/lazy to look it up atm. sue me.) made my combine... and didn't get a skill increase. And that for me was the end of the concordance bit right there. Bought me skill points from there.<br><br>Now while you do make friends getting components, you can make friends in EQ wherever you go. And there are plenty of excuses for passing through South Ro without resorting to greenie farming. My personal objection to the concordance quests is that you have to spend several hours rounding up parts and then pray to whatever dieties you believe in that you MIGHT actually get a skill increase from it. That, or you can just buy 5 skill increases per level and use that time to make enough cash to offset the cost.<br><br>I do understand your point about using it to make friends, but trust me. There are less painful ways. Tradeskills, research included, are a pain in the arse. Difference is, with other trade skills, when you get to a high enough skill, you become highly sought after and can make a ton of plat off it. With this, honestly the only time I REALLY needed the combine was for my level 49 pet spells. And post 49 there's nothing left to research. Yet anyway.<br><br>Right now the concordance quests, while you may personally find them fun, are frankly taking up time that could be better spent in other ways.<br><br>You are of course entitled to your opinion, and I do credit ya for playing devil's advocate on this.<br><br>One interesting thing you did mention is having your pet attack an add while you and your party finish the main mob off. That tatic is refered to (on povar at least) as off tanking, and is something mages excel at. At higher levels mage pets have quite a chunk of HP and can usually take a beating long enough for your group to finish any adds you run into. Just be careful doing this aroud chanters. Messes up their mezes. <br><br>As long as your pet holds the aggro and you drop a heal on it every now and then, off tanking's a skill that can serve you well all the way up to 60. Plus pets regen a lot faster than PCs, so every bit of damage a mob does to your pet opposed to your party is that much less downtime.<br><br>Anyhoo, in short, do the concordance stuff if ya want, just keep in mind that with all the time you spend on it you could be raising a trade skill that will actually make you some money down the road. And friends in this game aren't too hard to come by =)<br><br><br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, the Mad Mage of Povar<br>53rd season, leader of the Defiant Heroes[tm], arch nemesis of the evil squirrel empire.<br><br>PS: also paragraph breaks are something you may want to consider in future posts. Makes things a LOT easier to read. =)<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Sep 28 04:46:06 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
